2022… i feel different at the end of this year. 

my word of the year was “open-handed.” i wasn’t really sure what that word would look like played out but now i see so clearly what it meant. 
it wasn’t just a posture of receiving, although i received many good things. things i waited for, like our house after months and months of offers and getting second place. it was such a gift to finally receive our home 🫶🏽

open handed was also a posture of letting go. i let go & released a lot more things this year. i released the idea of being better or out-performing myself from last year. i was really at peace with more rest & breaks & slowing down in my business than ever since starting photography. 
i released myself from anxietized, self-created pressures that don’t serve me.

then i replaced those things with finding a lot of simple joys in my day to day. i turned inward & did a lot of hard work on myself this year to peel back & release inner parts of me that have been calling the shots in my mind & my thoughts. i’m really proud of myself for what i pressed into & progress i made in therapy & in real life opportunities. 

i released (and keep trying to) the idea of when our family would start & what that journey would be like, but have been seeking who i want to become in the process & hardship of it. 
i can’t explain how but it’s made me find gratitude for it all, which i never could have predicted. 

there have been lots of beautiful views & highlight moments that i captured, but i have to say i have loved the simple slower down iphone photo moments more than any of them (i put some of those in the last slide). 

even in the hardest days, i have so much to be thankful about🤍

big changes this year.
cross-country move, new home, new state, new cities traveled & new people met. now a new market for my business & new challenges presented. ready for it ✌🏽

i used to be so scared of boundaries. in my mind, boundaries meant i’d upset my clients & i was so afraid of getting one bad review & my business being canceled 😅

so i went way too many years running a business without boundaries to protect my self, especially my mental health. people pleasing was my default 😩

i don’t regret making mistakes in my business that leads me to learning valuable lessons but the thing i DO regret is not valuing myself enough to put healthy boundaries in place much earlier. your business is not at risk with boundaries. it sets you up to have necessary space between you as a human and you as a business owner. it’s really hard and yet it’s so incredibly worth fighting for!! 

so yeah, no boundaries expired in 2019* for this girl😎✌🏽

3 reasons to change your dress at your reception!
1. you’ll be more comfortable to dance without a heavy train & the weight of your wedding dress. you’ll also be free to change to a sneaker and your feet will thank you!
2. it adds fun variety to your gallery! all the formal stuff is in your wedding dress, so just as dancing gets going, you’ll spice up the end of the night photos with something unique. 
3. there are sooo many affordable dress options out there to make this possible! you can go a ton of directions with this & have fun with it :)

this one’s for the person who thought their business would be constant linear growth and improvement… 
for the person who expected last year to be different, definitely better, but it’s not. this is for the person who has watched someone else climb quickly & expected you would follow suit. or for the person who has compared your journey to someone else’s & you’re down on yourself for not accomplishing the same amount at the same pace. this is for the person who is doing their best to plan & strategize & keep control over something that really you can’t. this is for the person trying to pivot & shift & who is battling the fear of “what if” every day.   that was all me at various times. some even recently. && i’ve learned a really valuable lesson in the uniqueness of MY story, my growth, and my journey being solely my own. no one else will ever run the same business as me. so i get to enjoy the ride of how mine plays out, knowing it’s exactly how it should be. the ups are fun to celebrate and the lows are lessons for us to learn. there’s really not a lose lose when you realize that. :) 

it ebbs and flows. it just does. every single person can attest to this- it’s never straight up. and it’s OK and it’s NORMAL and RIGHT that it’s up and down, up and down. embrace the flow & stop clenching onto the expectation that you’re doing it wrong if it’s constantly & always going up. unclench your business jaw & trust the process. it’s unfolding for you uniquely. 🤍
 business is not the identity of your being. it doesn’t reflect who you are to the core and it doesn’t define you as successful or unsuccessful. so the comparing, the expectations, the belief in constant upward growth is all a distraction and a lie. you are where you’re meant to be. and look how far you’ve come!! it’s astounding! don’t lose sight of the journey you’ve already come from because you’re dying to rush to the next place. it’s a marathon, not a sprint. you’re doing amazing!

hi, posting for the first time on my feed in what feels like forever in business world terms!!

a couple things about me this summer- i have next to no weddings for 3 months. yep! you heard that right. none haha. because of our big move last year & the way my bookings were scheduled, i’m wide open. 

i didn’t stress about it, i’m just letting this be a wonderful break i’ve never had since starting this business. & i wanted to share about it openly because my gut tells me some people would never believe i’d have such an un-booked summer. but it’s true! & i’m totally good with that. in fact, strangely happy about it 🥲 soaking in these travels & just exploring our new michigan summer life. 

i’ve also realized (yet again) how valuable multiple streams of income are as people, let alone entrepreneurs. i stepped into a new income stream in january and have never been more grateful to keep expanding. otherwise, yes, i might be less comfortable in my open calendar. 

here to normalize the ebb and flow of this industry. not everyone you see is booked to the nines with work year after year. i’ve learned to go with the flow without stressing about it generally & i’m so at peace with the way things fall in my business. 

lastly & kind of randomly…my bestie took these photos of me in scotland unplanned. i didn’t dress for a shoot or change my hair or make up for it & i have to say i feel like myself more than ever in these images. getting all done up for photos might just be overrated…what do you think? ever tried to get perfect for a shoot & still picked yourself apart? try something spontaneous & see how ya feel:) 

that’s all✌🏽if you see me quieter around this page this summer you know why! i’m active over at @heyashtynbrooke if you miss me hehe

2023- you’ve been the year i, by and large, just didn’t expect…on both sides of the spectrum. good and hard. 
you carried in really amazing change. really beautiful change that i’ve hoped for for years. you were the year of settling into our community & space here in michigan that i’ve prayed for. and i love it. i’m so grateful for it. 
2023, also brought new work changes for both will & i. both ultimately good & better & best, though most of it unforeseen. i didn’t expect to be slowing down my photography business at this speed & im working through what that means, looks like, & feels. 
you brought the year of a new decade, 30, which i’ve welcomed with open arms. a big time stamp that also comes with a sort of life evaluation, for better or worse. 

2023 has also been the year i hoped everything would change, that our family would finally expand & it was yet again, not the year. i had the lowest of lows in this journey in 2023. lows i never thought i’d ever see. and more grief-filled questions i am tired of asking. i feel like i’m looking back on this year, partly picking up some pieces of my heart while also marveling at a lot of beautiful memories made, places traveled & time spent with worthwhile people. it would be a disservice to myself to only see the hard, heavy & lonely points.

& i think that might just be part of every year for the rest of my life. that exact juxtaposition. a mixture of beautiful and devastating. the way two opposing things can be held in the same space. for sure, that’s you, 2023.

a wild one. so many miles traveled, new places explored, memories banked & lessons acquired. more fantastic & dream weddings added to my career, & a new decade of life entered. added a new stream of income, started a podcast, read more, renovated more of our home (still loving that as a new hobby) & challenged myself to consistency in the gym for the first time in my life. not much of this year was very easy on me. i’m proud of who ashtyn was in 2023🤍

with grief, joy, gratitude, humility & definitely tears, it’s surreal to say that 2023 is my last full time year as a wedding photographer🤍🤍
this has been on my heart for most of this year, & i am following what i believe to be the best move forward for myself & our family. it is strange to sit on my couch & write this out with no one around. i’m just my own boss, trying to make the best decisions for my own business. it feels like “retirement” from what has been my heart, soul & passion for 7 straight years full time (& several before that as my hobby turned into an unforeseen career).

i feel like i have no words & a million to say all at once. it’s just impossible to put in a single caption/post what this job has meant to me, the opportunities it’s brought, & the people that have beautifully entered my world because of it. it literally changed my life in every sense. 

i am thee luckiest girl to have had this chance to grow in 1000 ways & learn more about myself than i thought possible. i’ve had so much support it doesn’t even make sense. swipe to the last photo which is my very first wedding with my #1 by my side. he had 0 freaking clue what to do but showed up to be by my side regardless. i wouldn’t be anywhere without him. & jesus- giving me this greatest gift & abundant , beautiful life.

my clients have been off the charts the best humans. i can’t believe they chose me to document their best days. if you’re one of my clients from any shoot or wedding ever, i love you. thank you for believing in me. i treasure you. 

i just have so much gratitude. i am honored & humbled by every moment of this ride. my heart breaks at the same time to wrap up this chapter. but we are turning the page in faith🤍
